class:: AutoWahCh
summary:: Envelope-followed peaking filter based on the chowdsp_utils AutoWah example
categories:: UGens>Effects
related:: Guides/ChowDSPPorts

Description::

AutoWahCh follows the `AutoWah` example from chowdsp_utils. The effect is built from two pieces: an envelope follower measures recent signal level, and that control signal drives the center frequency of a peaking filter. In DSP terms it is a time-varying filter whose coefficients depend on a smoothed estimate of signal amplitude, so strong attacks open the filter and decays let it fall back.

That is the classic auto-wah idea heard on funk guitar, clavinet, and percussive synth lines. Compared with a manually swept wah, this version feels more reactive than gestural: the brightness and vocal emphasis come from the player's dynamics or the input signal contour itself.

definitionlist::
## freq: || base wah frequency in Hz, intended range `200..2000`
## q: || peaking-filter Q, intended range `1..15`
## gainDB: || peaking-filter gain in dB, intended range `0..12`
## attackMs: || level-detector attack time in milliseconds, intended range `0.1..10`
## releaseMs: || level-detector release time in milliseconds, intended range `2.5..250`
## freqMod: || normalized sweep amount, intended range `0..1`
::

Unlike the JUCE example, this standalone port is mono-per-instance and does not expose the plugin editor. SC multichannel expansion still works normally.

classmethods::

method::ar

argument::in
Input signal.

argument::freq
Base wah frequency in Hz.

argument::q
Filter Q value.

argument::gainDB
Filter boost in dB.

argument::attackMs
Envelope follower attack time in milliseconds.

argument::releaseMs
Envelope follower release time in milliseconds.

argument::freqMod
Normalized sweep amount in `0..1`.

argument::mul
Output multiplier.

argument::add
Output offset.


